<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0106</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0106.</DOCID><HL>   Officer of Failed Bank   Based in Rhode Island   Charged With Fraud</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)RHODE ISLAND (RI)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- A vice president of Heritage Loan andamp;Investment Co., a small bank whose failure precipitated aRhode Island banking crisis, was arrested and charged withfraud, said a spokesman for Rhode Island Attorney GeneralJames E. O'Neil.   The executive, Peter J. Iannuccilli, allegedly helpedcover up bogus loans made to Joseph Mollicone Jr., thedefunct bank's president. Mr. Mollicone, who disappeared lastNovember and hasn't been heard from since, has been chargedwith embezzling $13 million from Heritage.</LP><TEXT>   News of Mr. Mollicone's disappearance sparked a run onHeritage last November. To cover withdrawals, the RhodeIsland Share andamp; Deposit Indemnity Corp., or Risdic, whichinsures credit unions and small banks in the state, had topump more than $14.6 million into Heritage. That drained theinsurer's funds, helped spark a run on other banks and,eventually, prompted Rhode Island officials to close 45 banksand credit unions insured by Risdic. Some of the bankinginstitutions remain closed.   Mr. Iannuccilli wasn't immediately available for comment.   The spokesman for Attorney General O'Neil said Mr.Iannuccilli was arrested at his home in Cranston, R.I.,charged and then released on his own recognizance. He couldreceive a prison term of as many as 20 years if convicted ofthe fraud charge, the spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>